# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: firewall-concepts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] There are multiple ways to acquire packets for deep packet inspection.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Using port mirroring (sometimes called Span Port) is a very common way, as well as physically inserting a network tap which duplicates and sends the data stream to an analyzer tool for inspection.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection (and filtering) enables advanced network management, user service, and security functions as well as Internet data mining, eavesdropping, and censorship.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Although DPI has been used for Internet management for many years, some advocates of net neutrality fear that the technique may be used anticompetitively or to reduce the openness of the Internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI is used in a wide range of applications, at the “enterprise level” (according to corporations and larger institutions), telecommunications service providers, and governments.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI technology has a long and technologically advanced history, starting in the 1990s, before the technology entered what is seen today as common, mainstream deployments.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Essential DPI functionality includes analysis of packet headers and protocol fields.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] For example, Wireshark offers essential DPI functionality through its numerous dissectors that display field names and content and, in some cases, offer interpretation of field values.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Some security solutions that offer DPI combine the functionality of an intrusion detection system (IDS) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS) with a traditional stateful firewall.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] This combination makes it possible to detect certain attacks that neither the IDS/IPS nor the stateful firewall can catch on their own.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Stateful firewalls, while able to see the beginning and end of a packet flow, cannot catch events on their own that would be out of bounds for a particular application.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] While IDSs are able to detect intrusions, they have very little capability in blocking such an attack.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPIs are used to prevent attacks from viruses and worms at wire speeds.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] More specifically, DPI can be effective against buffer overflow attacks, denial-of-service attacks (DoS), sophisticated intrusions, and a small percentage of worms that fit within a single packet.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI-enabled devices have the ability to look at Layer 2 and beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In some cases, DPI can be invoked to look through Layer 2-7 of the OSI model.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] This includes headers and data protocol structures as well as the payload of the message.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI functionality is invoked when a device looks or takes other action based on information beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI can identify and classify traffic based on a signature database that includes information extracted from the data part of a packet, allowing finer control than classification based only on header information.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] End points can utilize encryption and obfuscation techniques to evade DPI actions in many cases.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] A classified packet may be redirected, marked/tagged (see quality of service), blocked, rate limited, and of course, reported to a reporting agent in the network.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In this way, HTTP errors of different classifications may be identified and forwarded for analysis.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Many DPI devices can identify packet flows (rather than packet-by-packet analysis), allowing control actions based on accumulated flow information.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Initially security at the enterprise level was just a perimeter discipline, with a dominant philosophy of keeping unauthorized users out, and shielding authorized users from the outside world.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The most frequently used tool for accomplishing this has been a stateful firewall.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] It can permit fine-grained control of access from the outside world to pre-defined destinations on the internal network, as well as permitting access back to other hosts only if a request to the outside world has been made previously.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Vulnerabilities exist at network layers, however, that are not visible to a stateful firewall.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Firewalls also do not distinguish between permitted and forbidden uses of legitimately-accessed applications.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI enables IT administrators and security officials to set policies and enforce them at all layers, including the application and user layer to help combat those threats.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is able to detect a few kinds of buffer overflow attacks.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI may be used by enterprise for Data Leak Prevention (DLP).
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] When an e-mail user tries to send a protected file, the user may be given information on how to get the proper clearance to send the file.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI to secure their internal networks, Internet service providers (ISPs) also apply it on the public networks provided to customers.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Common uses of DPI by ISPs are lawful intercept, policy definition and enforcement, targeted advertising, quality of service, offering tiered services, and copyright enforcement.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers are required by almost all governments worldwide to enable lawful intercept capabilities.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Decades ago in a legacy telephone environment, this was met by creating a traffic access point (TAP) using an intercepting proxy server that connects to the government's surveillance equipment.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The acquisition component of this functionality may be provided in many ways, including DPI, DPI-enabled products that are "LI or CALEA-compliant" can be used – when directed by a court order – to access a user's datastream.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In some countries the ISPs are required to perform filtering, depending on the country's laws.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows service providers to "readily know the packets of information you are receiving online—from e-mail, to websites, to sharing of music, video and software downloads".
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Because ISPs route the traffic of all of their customers, they are able to monitor web-browsing habits in a very detailed way allowing them to gain information about their customers' interests, which can be used by companies specializing in targeted advertising.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] At least 100,000 United States customers are tracked this way, and as many as 10% of U.S. customers have been tracked in this way.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Technology providers include NebuAd, Front Porch, and Phorm.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs monitoring their customers include Knology and Wide Open West.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In addition, the United Kingdom ISP British Telecom has admitted testing solutions from Phorm without their customers' knowledge or consent.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Applications such as peer-to-peer (P2P) traffic present increasing problems for broadband service providers.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Typically, P2P traffic is used by applications that do file sharing.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] These may be any kind of files (i.e. documents, music, videos, or applications).
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Due to the frequently large size of media files being transferred, P2P drives increasing traffic loads, requiring additional network capacity.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers say a minority of users generate large quantities of P2P traffic and degrade performance for the majority of broadband subscribers using applications such as e-mail or Web browsing which use less bandwidth.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Poor network performance increases customer dissatisfaction and leads to a decline in service revenues.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows the operators to oversell their available bandwidth while ensuring equitable bandwidth distribution to all users by preventing network congestion.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Additionally, a higher priority can be allocated to a VoIP or video conferencing call which requires low latency versus web browsing which does not.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] This is the approach that service providers use to dynamically allocate bandwidth according to traffic that is passing through their networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Mobile and broadband service providers use DPI as a means to implement tiered service plans, to differentiate "walled garden" services from "value added", "all-you-can-eat" and "one-size-fits-all" data services.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs are sometimes requested by copyright owners or required by courts or official policy to help enforce copyrights.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, one of Denmark's largest ISPs, Tele2, was given a court injunction and told it must block its customers from accessing The Pirate Bay, a launching point for BitTorrent.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Instead of prosecuting file sharers one at a time, the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) and the big four record labels EMI, Sony BMG, Universal Music, and Warner Music have sued ISPs such as Eircom for not doing enough about protecting their copyrights.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA), which aims to enforce movie copyrights, has taken the position with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) that network neutrality could hurt anti-piracy techniques such as deep packet inspection and other forms of filtering.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI for the security of their own networks, governments in North America, Europe, and Asia use DPI for various purposes such as surveillance and censorship.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The Chinese government uses deep packet inspection to monitor and censor network traffic and content that it claims is harmful to Chinese citizens or state interests.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] This material includes pornography, information on religion, and political dissent.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Chinese network ISPs use DPI to see if there is any sensitive keyword going through their network.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] China previously blocked all VoIP traffic in and out of their country but many available VoIP applications now function in China.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Voice traffic in Skype is unaffected, although text messages are subject to filtering, and messages containing sensitive material, such as curse-words, are simply not delivered, with no notification provided to either participant in the conversation.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] China also blocks visual media sites such as YouTube.com and various photography and blogging sites.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Since 2015, Egypt reportedly started to join the list which was constantly being denied by the Egyptian National Telecom Regulatory Authority (NTRA) officials.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] However, it came to news when the country decided to block the encrypted messaging app Signal as announced by the application's developer.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In April 2017, all VoIP applications including FaceTime, Facebook Messenger, Viber, WhatsApp calls and Skype have been all blocked in the country.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] As of 2022, FaceTime, Facebook Messenger are unblocked.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The Indian ISP Jio, which is also the largest network operator in India has been known to employ sophisticated DPI techniques like SNI-based filtering to enforce censorship.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The Indonesian government via Telkom Indonesia, supported by Cisco Meraki DPI technology, perform country-wide surveillance by the way of deep packet inspection, and map it into SSN/NIK (Nomor Induk Kependudukan) of its citizens that registered to the state-owned ISP.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of deep packet inspection including filtering porn, hate speech, and reducing tension in West Papua.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Indonesian Government planned to scale up the surveillance to next level until 2030.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] According to unnamed experts cited in the article, the system "enables authorities to not only block communication but to monitor it to gather information about individuals, as well as alter it for disinformation purposes".
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The system was purchased by the Telecommunication Infrastructure Co., part of the Iranian government's telecom monopoly.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] According to the *Journal*, NSN "provided equipment to Iran last year under the internationally recognized concept of 'lawful intercept,' said Mr.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] That relates to intercepting data for the purposes of combating terrorism, child pornography, drug trafficking, and other criminal activities carried out online, a capability that most if not all telecom companies have, he said....
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] He said the company determined it was no longer part of its core business.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The NSN system followed on purchases by Iran from Secure Computing Corp. earlier in the decade.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Questions have been raised about the reporting reliability of the *Journal* report by David Isenberg, an independent Washington, D.C.–based analyst and Cato Institute Adjunct Scholar, specifically saying that Mr.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Roome is denying the quotes attributed to him and that he, Isenberg, also had similar complaints with one of the same *Journal* reporters in an earlier story.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] NSN has issued the following denial: NSN "has not provided any deep packet inspection, web censorship or Internet filtering capability to Iran".
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] A concurrent article in *The New York Times* stated the NSN sale had been covered in a "spate of news reports in April [2009], including *The Washington Times*," and reviewed censorship of the Internet and other media in the country, but did not mention DPI.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] According to Walid Al-Saqaf, the developer of the internet censorship circumventor Alkasir, Iran was using deep packet inspection in February 2012, bringing internet speeds in the entire country to a near standstill.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] This briefly eliminated access to tools such as Tor and Alkasir.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The incumbent Malaysian government, headed by Barisan Nasional, was said to be using DPI against a political opponent during the run-up to the 13th general elections held on 5 May 2013.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of DPI, in this instance, was to block and/or hinder access to selected websites, e.g.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Facebook accounts, blogs and news portals.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) states that the DPI system has been installed to implement the Prevention of Electronic Crimes Act (PECA) 2016, particularly to filter and block blasphemous content and any material that is considered to be against the integrity or security of Pakistan.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Canadian firm Sandvine was contracted to provide and set up the equipment in Pakistan.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Federal Law No.139 enforces blocking websites on the Russian Internet blacklist using IP filtering, but does not force ISPs into analyzing the data part of packets.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Yet some ISPs still use different DPI solutions to implement blacklisting.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] For 2019, the governmental agency Roskomnadzor is planning a nationwide rollout of DPI after the pilot project in one of the country's regions, at an estimated cost of 20 billion roubles (US$300M).
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The city state reportedly employs deep packet inspection of Internet traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] FCC adopts Internet CALEA requirements: The FCC, pursuant to its mandate from the U.S.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Congress, and in line with the policies of most countries worldwide, has required that all telecommunication providers, including Internet services, be capable of supporting the execution of a court order to provide real-time communication forensics of specified users.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, the FCC adopted new Title 47, Subpart Z, rules requiring Internet Access Providers to meet these requirements.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] DPI was one of the platforms essential to meeting this requirement and has been deployed for this purpose throughout the U.S.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The National Security Agency (NSA), with cooperation from AT&T Inc., has used deep packet inspection to make internet traffic surveillance, sorting, and forwarding more intelligent.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The DPI is used to find which packets are carrying e-mail or a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) telephone call.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Traffic associated with AT&T's Common Backbone was "split" between two fibers, dividing the signal so that 50 percent of the signal strength went to each output fiber.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] One of the output fibers was diverted to a secure room; the other carried communications on to AT&T's switching equipment.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The secure room contained Narus traffic analyzers and logic servers; Narus states that such devices are capable of real-time data collection (recording data for consideration) and capture at 10 gigabits per second.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Certain traffic was selected and sent over a dedicated line to a "central location" for analysis.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] According to an affidavit by expert witness J.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Narus's Semantic Traffic Analyzer software, which runs on IBM or Dell Linux servers using DPI, sorts through IP traffic at 10 Gbit/s to pick out specific messages based on a targeted e-mail address, IP address or, in the case of VoIP, telephone number.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Gonzales have asserted that they believe the president has the authority to order secret intercepts of telephone and e-mail exchanges between people inside the United States and their contacts abroad without obtaining a FISA warrant.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] The Defense Information Systems Agency has developed a sensor platform that uses deep packet inspection.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Vietnam launched its network security center and required ISPs to upgrade their hardware systems to use deep packet inspection to block Internet traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is considered by many to undermine the infrastructure of the internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] There is a greater emphasis being placed on deep packet inspection - this comes in light after the rejection of both the SOPA and PIPA bills.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Many current DPI methods are slow and costly, especially for high bandwidth applications.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] More efficient methods of DPI are being developed.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Specialized routers are now able to perform DPI; routers armed with a dictionary of programs will help identify the purposes behind the LAN and internet traffic they are routing.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] Cisco Systems is now on their second iteration of DPI enabled routers, with their announcement of the CISCO ISR G2 router.
[src:firewall-concepts/deep-packet-inspection] A comprehensive comparison of various network traffic classifiers, which depend on deep packet inspection (PACE, OpenDPI, 4 different configurations of L7-filter, NDPI, Libprotoident, and Cisco NBAR), is shown in the Independent Comparison of Popular DPI Tools for Traffic Classification.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] In computing, a **firewall** is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on configurable security rules.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] A firewall typically establishes a barrier between a trusted network and an untrusted network, such as the Internet or between several VLANs.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Firewalls can be categorized as network-based or host-based.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The term *firewall* originally referred to a wall to confine a fire within a line of adjacent buildings.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Later uses refer to similar structures, such as the metal sheet separating the engine compartment of a vehicle or aircraft from the passenger compartment.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The term was applied in the 1980s to network technology that emerged when the Internet was fairly new in terms of its global use and connectivity.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The predecessors to firewalls for network security were routers used in the 1980s.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Because they already segregated networks, routers could filter packets crossing them.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Before it was used in real-life computing, the term appeared in John Badham's 1983 computer‑hacking movie *WarGames*, spoken by the bearded and bespectacled programmer named Paul Richter, which possibly inspired its later use.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] One of the earliest commercially successful firewall and network address translation (NAT) products was the PIX (Private Internet eXchange) Firewall, invented in 1994 by Network Translation Inc., a startup founded and run by John Mayes.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The PIX Firewall technology was coded by Brantley Coile as a consultant software developer.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Recognizing the emerging IPv4 address depletion problem, they designed the PIX to enable organizations to securely connect private networks to the public internet using a limited number of registered IP addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The innovative PIX solution quickly gained industry acclaim, earning the prestigious "Hot Product of the Year" award from Data Communications Magazine in January 1995.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Cisco Systems, seeking to expand into the rapidly growing network security market, subsequently acquired Network Translation Inc. in November 1995 to obtain the rights to the PIX technology.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The PIX became one of Cisco's flagship firewall product lines before eventually being succeeded by the Adaptive Security Appliance (ASA) platform introduced in 2005.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Firewalls are categorized as a network-based or a host-based system.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Network-based firewalls are positioned between two or more networks, typically between the local area network (LAN) and wide area network (WAN), their basic function being to control the flow of data between connected networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] They are either a software appliance running on general-purpose hardware, a hardware appliance running on special-purpose hardware, or a virtual appliance running on a virtual host controlled by a hypervisor.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Firewall appliances may also offer non-firewall functionality, such as DHCP or VPN services.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Host-based firewalls are deployed directly on the host itself to control network traffic or other computing resources.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] This can be a daemon or service as a part of the operating system or an agent application for protection.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The first reported type of network firewall is called a packet filter which inspects packets transferred between computers.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The firewall maintains an access-control list which dictates what packets will be looked at and what action should be applied, if any, with the default action set to silent discard.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Three basic actions regarding the packet consist of a silent discard, discard with Internet Control Message Protocol or TCP reset response to the sender, and forward to the next hop.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Packets may be filtered by source and destination IP addresses, protocol, or source and destination ports.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The first paper published on firewall technology was in 1987 when engineers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) developed filter systems known as packet filter firewalls.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] At AT&T Bell Labs, Bill Cheswick and Steve Bellovin continued their research in packet filtering and developed a working model for their own company based on their original first-generation architecture.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] In 1992, Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson released a paper on BSD Packet Filter (BPF) while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] From 1989 to 1990, three colleagues from AT&T Bell Laboratories, Dave Presotto, Janardan Sharma, and Kshitij Nigam, developed the second generation of firewalls, calling them circuit-level gateways.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard released an application firewall known as Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) in October 1993.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] This became the basis for Gauntlet firewall at Trusted Information Systems.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The key benefit of application layer filtering is that it can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port, or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] It can also provide unified security management including enforced encrypted DNS and virtual private networking.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Endpoint-based application firewalls function by determining whether a process should accept any given connection.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Application firewalls filter connections by examining the process ID of data packets against a rule set for the local process involved in the data transmission.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Application firewalls accomplish their function by hooking into socket calls to filter the connections between the application layer and the lower layers.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Application firewalls that hook into socket calls are also referred to as socket filters.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] At the core of a firewall's operation are the policies that govern its decision-making process.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] These policies, collectively known as firewall rules, are the specific guidelines that determine the traffic allowed or blocked across a network's boundaries.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Firewall rules are based on the evaluation of network packets against predetermined security criteria.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] A network packet, which carries data across networks, must match certain attributes defined in a rule to be allowed through the firewall.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Zones are logical segments within a network that group together devices with similar security requirements.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] By partitioning a network into zones, such as "Technical", "WAN", "LAN", "Public," "Private," "DMZ", and "Wireless," administrators can enforce policies that control the flow of traffic between them.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Each zone has its own level of trust and is governed by specific firewall rules that regulate the ingress and egress of data.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] A typical default is to allow all traffic from LAN to WAN, and to drop all traffic from WAN to LAN.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] In networking terms, services are specific functions typically identified by a network port and protocol.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Common examples include HTTP/HTTPS (web traffic) on ports 80 and 443, FTP (file transfer) on port 21, and SMTP (email) on port 25.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Services are the engines behind the applications users depend on.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] From a security aspect, controlling access to services is crucial because services are common targets for exploitation.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Firewalls employ rules that stipulate which services should be accessible, to whom, and in what context.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] For example, a firewall might be configured to block incoming FTP requests to prevent unauthorized file uploads but allow outgoing HTTPS requests for web browsing.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Applications refer to the software systems that users interact with while on the network.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] They can range from web browsers and email clients to complex database systems and cloud-based services.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] In network security, applications are important because different types of traffic can pose varying security risks.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Thus, firewall rules can be crafted to identify and control traffic based on the application generating or receiving it.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] By using application awareness, firewalls can allow, deny, or limit traffic for specific applications according to organizational policies and compliance requirements, thereby mitigating potential threats from vulnerable or undesired applications.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Application can both be a grouping of services, or a L7 inspection.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Implementing firewall rules based on IP addresses alone is often insufficient due to the dynamic nature of user location and device usage.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] User ID will be translated to an IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] This is where the concept of "User ID" makes a significant impact.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] User ID allows firewall rules to be crafted based on individual user identities, rather than just fixed source or destination IP addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] This enhances security by enabling more granular control over who can access certain network resources, regardless of where they are connecting from or what device they are using.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] The User ID technology is typically integrated into firewall systems through the use of directory services such as Active Directory, LDAP, RADIUS or TACACS+.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] These services link the user's login information to their network activities.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] By doing this, the firewall can apply rules and policies that correspond to user groups, roles, or individual user accounts instead of purely relying on the network topology.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Consider a school that wants to restrict access to a social media server from students.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] They can create a rule in the firewall that utilises User ID information to enforce this policy.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] User Identification — The firewall maps network traffic to specific user IDs by interpreting authentication logs.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] When a user logs on, the firewall associates that login with the user's IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Define User Groups — Within the firewall's management interface, define user groups based on the directory service.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] For example, create groups such as "Students".
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] With this setup, only users who authenticate and are identified as members of "Students" are denied to access social media servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] All other traffic, starting from LAN interfaces, will be allowed.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Setting up a firewall is a complex and error-prone task.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] A network may face security issues due to configuration errors.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Firewall policies are typically configured according to the type of network in use, such as public or private environments.
[src:firewall-concepts/firewall-computing] Administrators define rules that permit or restrict traffic in order to reduce exposure to threats like unauthorized access, malware, or other forms of cyberattack.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] As network address translation modifies the IP address information in packets, NAT implementations may vary in their specific behavior in various addressing cases and their effect on network traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Vendors of equipment containing NAT implementations do not commonly document the specifics of NAT behavior.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) uses 32-bit addresses, capable of uniquely addressing about 4.3 billion devices on the network.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] By 1992, it became evident that this would not be enough.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The 1994 RFC 1631 describes NAT as a "short-term solution" to the two most compelling problems facing the Internet Protocol at that time: IP address depletion and scaling in routing.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The technique also became known as **IP masquerading**, which suggests a technique that hides an entire IP address space, usually consisting of private IP addresses, behind a single IP address in another, usually public address space.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Because of the popularity of this technique to conserve IPv4 address space, the term *NAT* became virtually synonymous with IP masquerading.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In 1996, port-address translation (PAT) was introduced, which expanded the translation of addresses to include port numbers.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The simplest type of NAT provides a one-to-one translation of IP addresses (RFC 1631).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 refers to this type of NAT as *basic NAT*, also called a *one-to-one NAT*.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In this type of NAT, only the IP addresses, IP header checksum, and any higher-level checksums that include the IP address are changed.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Basic NAT can be used to interconnect two IP networks with incompatible addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Most network address translators map multiple private hosts to one publicly exposed IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In a typical configuration, a local network uses one of the designated *private* IP address subnets (RFC 1918).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The network has a router having network interfaces on both the private and the public networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The public address is typically assigned by an Internet service provider.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] As traffic passes from the private network to the Internet, NAT translates the source address in each packet from a private address to the router's public address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The NAT facility tracks each active connection.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] When the router receives inbound traffic from the Internet, it uses the connection tracking data obtained during the outbound phase to determine to which private address it should forward the reply.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Packets passing from the private network to the public network will have their source address modified, while packets passing from the public network back to the private network will have their destination address modified.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] To avoid ambiguity in how replies are translated, further modifications to the packets are required.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The vast bulk of Internet traffic uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For these protocols, the port numbers are changed so that the combination of IP address (within the IP header) and port number (within the Transport Layer header) on the returned packet can be unambiguously mapped to the corresponding private network destination.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 uses the term **network address and port translation** (**NAPT**) for this type of NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Other names include **port address translation** (**PAT**), *IP masquerading*, *NAT overload*, and *many-to-one NAT*.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This is the most common type of NAT and has become synonymous with the term *NAT* in common usage.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This method allows communication through the router only when the conversation originates in the private network, since the initial originating transmission establishes the required information in the translation tables.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Thus, a web browser within the private network is able to browse websites that are outside the network, whereas web browsers outside the network are unable to browse a website hosted within.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Protocols not based on TCP and UDP require other translation techniques.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The primary benefit of one-to-many NAT is mitigation of IPv4 address exhaustion by allowing entire networks to be connected to the Internet using a single public IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Network address and port translation may be implemented in several ways.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Some applications that use IP address information may need to determine the external address of a network address translator.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This is the address that its communication peers in the external network detect.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Furthermore, it may be necessary to examine and categorize the type of mapping in use, for example, when it is desired to set up a direct communication path between two clients, both of which are behind separate NAT gateways.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For this purpose, RFC 3489 specified the protocol *Simple Traversal of UDP over NATs* (STUN) in 2003.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] It classified NAT implementations as *full-cone NAT*, *(address) restricted-cone NAT*, *port-restricted cone NAT* or *symmetric NAT*, and proposed a methodology for testing a device accordingly.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] However, these procedures have since been deprecated from standards status, as the methods are inadequate to correctly assess many devices.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] RFC 5389 standardized new methods in 2008 and the acronym *STUN* since represents the new title of the specification: *Session Traversal Utilities for NAT*.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] As many NAT implementations combine multiple types, it is better to refer to specific individual NAT behavior instead of using the Cone/Symmetric terminology.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 attempts to alleviate confusion by introducing standardized terminology for observed behaviors.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For the first bullet in each row of the above table, the RFC would characterize Full-Cone, Restricted-Cone, and Port-Restricted-Cone NATs as having an *Endpoint-Independent Mapping*, whereas it would characterize a Symmetric NAT as having an *Address- and Port-Dependent Mapping*.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Other classifications of NAT behavior mentioned in the RFC include whether they preserve ports, when and how mappings are refreshed, whether external mappings can be used by internal hosts (i.e., its hairpinning behavior), and the level of determinism NATs exhibit when applying all these rules.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Specifically, most NATs combine *symmetric NAT* for outgoing connections with *static port mapping*, where incoming packets addressed to the external address and port are redirected to a specific internal address and port.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 distinguishes between NAT mapping and NAT filtering.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Section 4.1 of the RFC covers NAT mapping and specifies the translation of an external IP address and port number into an internal IP address and port number.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Section 5 of the RFC covers NAT filtering and describes the criteria used by the NAT to filter packets originating from specific external endpoints.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The options are endpoint-independent filtering, address-dependent filtering and address- and port-dependent filtering.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Endpoint-independent filtering is recommended where maximum application transparency is required while address-dependent filtering is recommended where more stringent filtering behavior is most important.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Some NAT devices are not compliant with RFC 4787 as they treat NAT mapping and filtering in the same way, so that their configuration option for changing the NAT filtering method also changes the NAT mapping method (e.g., Netgate TNSR Archived 2024-01-30 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] NAT traversal problems arise when peers behind different NATs try to communicate.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] One way to solve this problem is to use port forwarding.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Another way is to use various NAT traversal techniques.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The most popular technique for TCP NAT traversal is TCP hole punching.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] TCP hole punching requires the NAT to follow the *port preservation* design for TCP.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For a given outgoing TCP communication, the same port numbers are used on both sides of the NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] NAT port preservation for outgoing TCP connections is crucial for TCP NAT traversal because, under TCP, one port can only be used for one communication at a time.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Programs that bind distinct TCP sockets to ephemeral ports for each TCP communication make NAT port prediction impossible for TCP.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] On the other hand, for UDP, NATs do not need port preservation.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Indeed, multiple UDP communications (each with a distinct endpoint) can occur on the same source port, and applications usually reuse the same UDP socket to send packets to distinct hosts.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This makes port prediction straightforward, as it is the same source port for each packet.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Furthermore, port preservation in NAT for TCP allows P2P protocols to offer less complexity and less latency because there is no need to use a third party (like STUN) to discover the NAT port since the application itself already knows the NAT port.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Every TCP and UDP packet contains a source port number and a destination port number.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Each of those packets is encapsulated in an IP packet, whose IP header contains a source IP address and a destination IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The IP address/protocol/port number triple defines an association with a network socket.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For publicly accessible services such as web and mail servers, the port number is important.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For example, port 443 connects through a socket to the web server software and port 465 to a mail server's SMTP daemon.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The IP address of a public server is also important, similar in global uniqueness to a postal address or telephone number.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Both the IP address and port number must be correctly known by all hosts wishing to communicate successfully.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Private IP addresses as described in RFC 1918, are usable only on private networks not directly connected to the Internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Ports are endpoints of communication unique to that host, so a connection through the NAT device is maintained by the combined mapping of port and IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] A private address on the inside of the NAT is mapped to an external public address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Port address translation (PAT) resolves conflicts that arise when multiple hosts happen to use the same source port number to establish different external connections at the same time.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] With NAT, all communications sent to external hosts actually contain the *external* IP address and port information of the NAT device instead of internal host IP addresses or port numbers.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] NAT only translates IP addresses and ports of its internal hosts, hiding the true endpoint of an internal host on a private network.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] When a computer on the private (internal) network sends an IP packet to the external network, the NAT device replaces the internal source IP address in the packet header with the external IP address of the NAT device.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] PAT may then assign the connection a port number from a pool of available ports, inserting this port number in the source port field.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The packet is then forwarded to the external network.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The NAT device then makes an entry in a translation table containing the internal IP address, original source port, and the translated source port.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Subsequent packets from the same internal source IP address and port number are translated to the same external source IP address and port number.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The computer receiving a packet that has undergone NAT establishes a connection to the port and IP address specified in the altered packet, oblivious to the fact that the supplied address is being translated.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Upon receiving a packet from the external network, the NAT device searches the translation table based on the destination port in the packet header.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If a match is found, the destination IP address and port number are replaced with the values found in the table and the packet is forwarded to the inside network.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Otherwise, if the destination port number of the incoming packet is not found in the translation table, the packet is dropped or rejected because the PAT device doesn't know where to send it.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Network address translation can be used to mitigate IP address overlap.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Address overlap occurs when hosts in different networks with the same IP address space try to reach the same destination host.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The destination host experiences traffic apparently arriving from the same network, and intermediate routers have no way to determine where reply traffic should be sent to.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The solution is either renumbering to eliminate overlap or network address translation.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] forward client requests to a set of server computers to manage the workload of each server.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Network address translation may be used to map a representative IP address of the server cluster to specific hosts that service the request.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] IEEE Reverse Address and Port Translation (RAPT or RAT) allows a host whose real IP address changes from time to time to remain reachable as a server via a fixed home IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Cisco's RAPT implementation is PAT or NAT overloading and maps multiple private IP addresses to a single public IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Multiple addresses can be mapped to a single address because each private address is tracked by a port number.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] PAT uses unique source port numbers on the inside global IP address to distinguish between translations.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] PAT attempts to preserve the original source port.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If this source port is already used, PAT assigns the first available port number starting from the beginning of the appropriate port group 0–511, 512–1023, or 1024–65535.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] When there are no more ports available and there is more than one external IP address configured, PAT moves to the next IP address to try to allocate the original source port again.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This process continues until it runs out of available ports and external IP addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Mapping of Address and Port is a Cisco proposal that combines Address plus Port translation with tunneling of the IPv4 packets over an ISP provider's internal IPv6 network.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In effect, it is an (almost) stateless alternative to carrier-grade NAT and DS-Lite that pushes the IPv4 address/port translation function (and the maintenance of NAT state) entirely into the existing customer premises equipment NAT implementation.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Thus avoiding the NAT444 and statefulness problems of carrier-grade NAT, and also provides a transition mechanism for the deployment of native IPv6 at the same time with very little added complexity.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Hosts behind NAT-enabled routers do not have end-to-end connectivity and cannot participate in some internet protocols.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Services that require the initiation of TCP connections from the outside network, or that use stateless protocols such as those using UDP, can be disrupted.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Unless the NAT router makes a specific effort to support such protocols, incoming packets cannot reach their destination.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Some protocols can accommodate one instance of NAT between participating hosts ("passive mode" FTP, for example), sometimes with the assistance of an application-level gateway (see § Applications affected by NAT), but fail when both systems are separated from the internet by NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The use of NAT also complicates tunneling protocols such as IPsec because NAT modifies values in the headers, which interfere with the integrity checks done by IPsec and other tunneling protocols.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] End-to-end connectivity has been a core principle of the Internet, supported, for example, by the Internet Architecture Board.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Current Internet architectural documents observe that NAT is a violation of the end-to-end principle, but that NAT does have a valid role in careful design.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] There is considerably more concern with the use of IPv6 NAT, and many IPv6 architects believe IPv6 was intended to remove the need for NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] An implementation that only tracks ports can be quickly depleted by internal applications that use multiple simultaneous connections, such as an HTTP request for a web page with many embedded objects.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This problem can be mitigated by tracking the destination IP address in addition to the port, thus sharing a single local port with many remote hosts.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This additional tracking increases implementation complexity and computing resources at the translation device.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Because the internal addresses are all disguised behind one publicly accessible address, it is impossible for external hosts to directly initiate a connection to a particular internal host.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Applications such as VOIP, videoconferencing, and other peer-to-peer applications must use NAT traversal techniques to function.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Pure NAT, operating on IP alone, may or may not correctly parse protocols with payloads containing information about IP, such as ICMP.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This depends on whether the payload is interpreted by a host on the *inside* or *outside* of the translation.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Basic protocols such as TCP and UDP cannot function properly unless NAT takes action beyond the network layer.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] IP packets have a checksum in each packet header, which provides error detection only for the header.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] IP datagrams may become fragmented and it is necessary for a NAT to reassemble these fragments to allow correct recalculation of higher-level checksums and correct tracking of which packets belong to which connection.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] TCP and UDP have a checksum that covers all the data they carry, as well as the TCP or UDP header, plus a *pseudo-header* that contains the source and destination IP addresses of the packet carrying the TCP or UDP header.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For an originating NAT to pass TCP or UDP successfully, it must recompute the TCP or UDP header checksum based on the translated IP addresses, not the original ones, and put that checksum into the TCP or UDP header of the first packet of the fragmented set of packets.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Alternatively, the originating host may perform path MTU Discovery to determine the packet size that can be transmitted without fragmentation and then set the *don't fragment* (DF) bit in the appropriate packet header field.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This is only a one-way solution, because the responding host can send packets of any size, which may be fragmented before reaching the NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Destination network address translation (DNAT) is a technique for transparently changing the destination IP address of a routed packet and performing the inverse function for any replies.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Any router situated between two endpoints can perform this transformation of the packet.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] DNAT is commonly used to publish a service located in a private network on a publicly accessible IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This use of DNAT is also called port forwarding, or DMZ when used on an entire server, which becomes exposed to the WAN, becoming analogous to an undefended military demilitarized zone (DMZ).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Secure network address translation (SNAT) is part of Microsoft's Internet Security and Acceleration Server and is an extension to the NAT driver built into Microsoft Windows Server.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] It provides connection tracking and filtering for the additional network connections needed for the FTP, ICMP, H.323, and PPTP protocols as well as the ability to configure a transparent HTTP proxy server.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Dynamic NAT, just like static NAT, is not common in smaller networks but is found within larger corporations with complex networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Where static NAT provides a one-to-one internal to public static IP address mapping, dynamic NAT uses a *group* of public IP addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If a packet is sent to *203.0.113.1* by a computer at *192.168.1.100*, the packet would normally be routed to the default gateway (the router).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] A router with the NAT loopback feature detects that *203.0.113.1* is the address of its WAN interface, and treats the packet as if coming from that interface.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] It determines the destination for that packet, based on DNAT (port forwarding) rules for the destination.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If the data were sent to port 80 and a DNAT rule exists for port 80 directed to *192.168.1.2*, then the host at that address receives the packet.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If no applicable DNAT rule is available, the router drops the packet.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] An ICMP Destination Unreachable reply may be sent.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If any DNAT rules were present, address translation is still in effect; the router still rewrites the source IP address in the packet.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Because the source address is part of the same broadcast domain as the server, it will respond with a packet destined directly to the local computer on layer 2, without involving the router.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] As the local computer did not expect any traffic from *192.168.1.2* (the local address of the server), but from *203.0.113.1*, the address that it actually intended to connect to, it will silently drop the response.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] To enable two-way communication using the external address between these hosts, an SNAT rule must be configured.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Such a rule specifies that traffic received from the local network and destined to the server (to its local address, after rewriting) should have its source address rewritten to an address of the router.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This way, the response of the server will be sent to the router, which is then able to apply the reverse SNAT and DNAT transformations and send the expected response back to the local computer.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Thus, two-way communication is possible between hosts inside the LAN network via the public IP address, as long as appropriate NAT rules are set up.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Network address translation is not commonly used in IPv6 because one of the design goals of IPv6 is to restore end-to-end network connectivity.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 obviates the need to conserve addresses and every device can be given a unique globally routable address.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Use of unique local addresses in combination with network prefix translation can achieve results similar to NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 can still be defeated, depending on the actual prefix length given by the carrier.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] It is not uncommon to be handed a /64 prefix – the smallest recommended subnet – for an entire home network, requiring a variety of techniques to be used to manually subdivide the range for all devices to remain reachable.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In such cases, it may be required to use full network address and port translation (NAPT) on IPv6, usually referred to as NAT66, where an IPv6 ULA prefix is masqueraded down to a single IPv6 global unique address (GUA).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The APNIC blog outlines a case where the author was only provided a single address (/128).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Some application layer protocols, such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP) and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), send explicit network addresses within their application data.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] File Transfer Protocol in active mode, for example, uses separate connections for control traffic (commands) and for data traffic (file contents).
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] When requesting a file transfer, the host making the request identifies the corresponding data connection by its network layer and transport layer addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If the host making the request lies behind a simple NAT firewall, the translation of the IP address or TCP port number makes the information received by the server invalid.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] SIP commonly controls voice over IP calls, and suffer the same problem.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] SIP and its accompanying Session Description Protocol may use multiple ports to set up a connection and transmit a voice stream via Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] IP addresses and port numbers are encoded in the payload data and must be known before the traversal of NATs.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Without special techniques, such as STUN, NAT behavior is unpredictable and communications may fail.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Application Layer Gateway (ALG) software or hardware may correct these problems.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] An ALG software module running on a NAT firewall device updates any payload data made invalid by address translation.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] ALGs need to understand the higher-layer protocol that they need to fix, and so each protocol with this problem requires a separate ALG.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] For example, on many Linux systems, there are kernel modules called *connection trackers* that serve to implement ALGs.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] However, ALG cannot work if the protocol data is encrypted.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Another possible solution to this problem is to use NAT traversal techniques using protocols such as STUN or Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE), or proprietary approaches in a session border controller.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] NAT traversal is possible in both TCP- and UDP-based applications, but the UDP-based technique is simpler, more widely understood, and more compatible with legacy NATs.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In either case, the high-level protocol must be designed with NAT traversal in mind, and it does not work reliably across symmetric NATs or other poorly behaved legacy NATs.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Other possibilities are Port Control Protocol (PCP), NAT Port Mapping Protocol (NAT-PMP), or Internet Gateway Device Protocol but these require the NAT device to implement that protocol.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Most client–server protocols (FTP being the main exception), however, do not send layer 3 contact information and do not require any special treatment by NATs.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In fact, avoiding NAT complications is practically a requirement when designing new higher-layer protocols today.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] NATs can also cause problems where IPsec encryption is applied and in cases where multiple devices, such as SIP phones are located behind a NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Phones that encrypt their signaling with IPsec encapsulate the port information within an encrypted packet, meaning that NAT devices cannot access and translate the port.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] In these cases, the NAT devices revert to simple NAT operations.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] This means that all traffic returning to the NAT is mapped onto one client, causing service to more than one client behind the NAT to fail.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE) is a NAT traversal technique that does not rely on ALG support.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The DNS protocol vulnerability announced by Dan Kaminsky on July 8, 2008, is indirectly affected by NAT port mapping.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] To avoid DNS cache poisoning, it is highly desirable not to translate UDP source port numbers of outgoing DNS requests from a DNS server behind a firewall that implements NAT.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] The recommended workaround for the DNS vulnerability is to make all caching DNS servers use randomized UDP source ports.
[src:firewall-concepts/network-address-translation] If the NAT function de-randomizes the UDP source ports, the DNS server becomes vulnerable.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] A **packet analyzer** (also **packet sniffer** or **network analyzer**) is a computer program or computer hardware such as a packet capture appliance that can analyze and log traffic that passes over a computer network or part of a network.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] **Packet capture** is the process of intercepting and logging traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] As data streams flow across the network, the analyzer captures each packet and, if needed, decodes the packet's raw data, showing the values of various fields in the packet, and analyzes its content according to the appropriate RFC or other specifications.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] A packet analyzer used for intercepting traffic on wireless networks is known as a **wireless analyzer**—those designed specifically for Wi-Fi networks are **Wi-Fi analyzers**.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] While a packet analyzer can also be referred to as a network analyzer or protocol analyzer, these terms can also have other meanings.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] The class of protocol analyzers can technically be a broader, more general class that includes packet analyzers and sniffers.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] However, the terms are frequently used interchangeably.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] On wired shared-medium networks, such as Ethernet, Token Ring, and FDDI, depending on the network structure (hub or switch), it may be possible to capture all traffic on the network from a single machine.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] On modern networks, traffic can be captured using a network switch using port mirroring, which mirrors all packets that pass through designated ports of the switch to another port, if the switch supports port mirroring.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] A network tap is an even more reliable solution than using a monitoring port since taps are less likely to drop packets during high traffic loads.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, traffic can be captured on one channel at a time, or by using multiple adapters, on several channels simultaneously.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] On wired broadcast and wireless LANs, to capture unicast traffic between other machines, the network adapter capturing the traffic must be in promiscuous mode.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] On wireless LANs, even if the adapter is in promiscuous mode, packets not for the service set the adapter is configured for are usually ignored.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] To see those packets, the adapter must be in monitor mode.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] No special provisions are required to capture multicast traffic to a multicast group the packet analyzer is already monitoring, or broadcast traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] When traffic is captured, either the entire contents of packets or just the headers are recorded.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Recording just headers reduces storage requirements and avoids some privacy legal issues, yet often provides sufficient information to diagnose problems.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Captured information is decoded from raw digital form into a human-readable format that lets engineers review exchanged information.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers vary in their abilities to display and analyze data.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Some packet analyzers can also generate traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Such testers generate protocol-correct traffic for functional testing, and may also have the ability to deliberately introduce errors to test the device under test's ability to handle errors.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Packet analyzers can also be hardware-based, either in probe format or, as is increasingly common, combined with a disk array.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] These devices record packets or packet headers to a disk array.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Packet capture can be used to fulfill a warrant from a law enforcement agency to wiretap all network traffic generated by an individual.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Internet service providers and VoIP providers in the United States must comply with Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act regulations.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Using packet capture and storage, telecommunications carriers can provide the legally required secure and separate access to targeted network traffic and can use the same device for internal security purposes.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] Collecting data from a carrier system without a warrant is illegal due to laws about interception.
[src:firewall-concepts/packet-analyzer] By using end-to-end encryption, communications can be kept confidential from telecommunication carriers and legal authorities.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] In computer networking, **port forwarding** or **port mapping** is an application of network address translation (NAT) that redirects a communication request from one address and port number combination to another while the packets are traversing a network gateway, such as a router or firewall.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] This technique is most commonly used to make services on a host residing on a protected or masqueraded (internal) network available to hosts on the opposite side of the gateway (external network), by remapping the destination IP address and port number of the communication to an internal host.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Port forwarding facilitates the connection by remote computers, for example, Internet hosts, to a specific computer or service within a local area network (LAN).
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] In a typical residential network, nodes obtain Internet access through a DSL or cable modem connected to a router or network address translator (NAT/NAPT).
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Hosts on the private network are connected to an Ethernet switch or communicate via a wireless LAN.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The NAT device's external interface is configured with a public IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The computers behind the router, on the other hand, are invisible to hosts on the Internet as they each communicate only with a private IP address.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] When configuring port forwarding, the network administrator sets aside one port number on the gateway for the exclusive use of communicating with a service in the private network, located on a specific host.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] External hosts must know this port number and the address of the gateway to communicate with the network-internal service.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Often, the port numbers of well-known Internet services, such as port number 80 for web services (HTTP), are used in port forwarding, so that common Internet services may be implemented on hosts within private networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Administrators configure port forwarding in the gateway's operating system.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] In Linux kernels, this is achieved by packet filter rules in the iptables or netfilter kernel components.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] BSD and macOS operating systems prior to Yosemite (OS 10.10.X) implement it in the Ipfirewall (ipfw) module while macOS operating systems beginning with Yosemite implement it in the Packet Filter (pf) module.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] When used on gateway devices, a port forward may be implemented with a single rule to translate the destination address and port.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The source address and port are, in this case, left unchanged.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] When used on machines that are not the default gateway of the network, the source address must be changed to be the address of the translating machine, or packets will bypass the translator and the connection will fail.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] When a port forward is implemented by a proxy process (such as on application layer firewalls, SOCKS based firewalls, or via TCP circuit proxies), then no packets are actually translated, only data is proxied.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] This usually results in the source address (and port number) being changed to that of the proxy machine.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Usually only one of the private hosts can use a specific forwarded port at one time, but configuration is sometimes possible to differentiate access by the originating host's source address.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Unix-like operating systems sometimes use port forwarding where port numbers smaller than 1024 can only be created by software running as the root user.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Running with superuser privileges (in order to bind the port) may be a security risk to the host, therefore port forwarding is used to redirect a low-numbered port to another high-numbered port, so that application software may execute as a common operating system user with reduced privileges.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The Universal Plug and Play protocol (UPnP) provides a feature to automatically install instances of port forwarding in residential Internet gateways.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] UPnP defines the Internet Gateway Device Protocol (IGD) which is a network service by which an Internet gateway advertises its presence on a private network via the Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP).
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] An application that provides an Internet-based service may discover such gateways and use the UPnP IGD protocol to reserve a port number on the gateway and cause the gateway to forward packets to its listening socket.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Port forwarding may be distinguished by the following specific types: local, remote, and dynamic port forwarding.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Local port forwarding is the most common type of port forwarding.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] It is used to let a user connect from the local computer to another server, i.e. forward data securely from another client application running on the same computer as a Secure Shell (SSH) client.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] By using local port forwarding, firewalls that block certain web pages, can be bypassed.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Connections from an SSH client are forwarded, via an SSH server, to the intended destination server.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The SSH server is configured to redirect data from a specified port (which is local to the host that runs the SSH client) through a secure tunnel to some specified destination host and port.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The local port is on the same computer as the SSH client, and this port is the "forwarded port".
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] On the same computer, any client that wants to connect to the same destination host and port can be configured to connect to the forwarded port (rather than directly to the destination host and port).
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] After this connection is established, the SSH client listens on the forwarded port and directs all data sent by applications to that port, through a secure tunnel to the SSH server.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The server decrypts the data, and then redirects it to the destination host and port.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] This form of port forwarding enables applications on the server side of a Secure Shell (SSH) connection to access services residing on the SSH's client side.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] In addition to SSH, there are proprietary tunneling schemes that utilize remote port forwarding for the same general purpose.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] In other words, remote port forwarding lets users connect from the server side of a tunnel, SSH or another, to a remote network service located at the tunnel's client side.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] To use remote port forwarding, the address of the destination server (on the tunnel's client side) and two port numbers must be known.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The port numbers chosen depend on which application is to be used.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Remote port forwarding allows other computers to access applications hosted on remote servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Simply speaking, when your laptop connects to a remote machine in such way, that incoming calls to the IP of that remote machine get transferred to your laptop - and response back.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Dynamic port forwarding (DPF) is an on-demand method of traversing a firewall or NAT through the use of firewall pinholes.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] The goal is to enable clients to connect securely to a trusted server that acts as an intermediary for the purpose of sending/receiving data to one or many destination servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] DPF can be implemented by setting up a local application, such as SSH, as a SOCKS proxy server, which can be used to process data transmissions through the network or over the Internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Programs, such as web browsers, must be configured individually to direct traffic through the proxy, which acts as a secure tunnel to another server.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Once the proxy is no longer needed, the programs must be reconfigured to their original settings.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Because of the manual requirements of DPF, it is not often used.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Once the connection is established, DPF can be used to provide additional security for a user connected to an untrusted network.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] Since data must pass through the secure tunnel to another server before being forwarded to its original destination, the user is protected from packet sniffing that may occur on the LAN.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] DPF is a powerful tool with many uses; for example, a user connected to the Internet through a coffee shop, hotel, or otherwise minimally secure network may wish to use DPF as a way of protecting data.
[src:firewall-concepts/port-forwarding] DPF can also be used to bypass firewalls that restrict access to outside websites, such as in corporate networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In computer networking, a **proxy server** is a intermediary server application between a client requesting a resource and the server then providing that resource.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server that can fulfil a request for a resource, such as a file or web page, the client directs the request to the proxy server, which evaluates the request and performs the required network transactions.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This serves as a method to control the complexity of the request or provide additional benefits such as load balancing, privacy or security.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Proxies were devised to add structure and encapsulation to distributed systems.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A proxy server may reside on the user's **local computer**, or at any point between the user's computer and the destination servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A proxy server that passes unmodified requests and responses is usually called a gateway or sometimes a *tunneling proxy*.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A forward proxy is an Internet-facing proxy used to retrieve data from a wide range of sources (in most cases, anywhere on the Internet).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A reverse proxy is usually an internal-facing proxy used as a front-end to control and protect access to a server on a private network.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A reverse proxy commonly also performs tasks such as load-balancing, authentication, decryption, and caching.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] An open proxy is a forwarding proxy server that is accessible by any Internet user.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In 2008, network security expert Gordon Lyon estimated that "hundreds of thousands" of open proxies are operated on the Internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A reverse proxy (or surrogate) is a proxy server that appears to clients to be an ordinary server.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Reverse proxies send requests to one or more ordinary servers that handle the request.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The response from the original server is returned as if it came directly from the proxy server, leaving the client with no knowledge of the original server.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Reverse proxies are installed in the vicinity of one or more web servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] All traffic coming from the Internet and with a destination of one of the neighborhood's web servers goes through the proxy server.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The use of "reverse" originates in its counterpart, the "forward" proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The reverse proxy sits closer to the web server and serves only a restricted set of websites.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A forward proxy is a server that routes traffic between clients and another system, which is, in most cases, external to the network.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This means it can regulate traffic according to preset policies, convert and mask client IP addresses, enforce security protocols, and block unknown traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A forward proxy enhances security and policy enforcement within an internal network.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A reverse proxy, instead of protecting the client, is used to protect the servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A reverse proxy accepts a request from a client, forwards that request to another one of many other servers, and then returns the results from the server that specifically processed the request to the client.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Effectively, a reverse proxy acts as a gateway between clients, users, and application servers and handles all the traffic routing whilst also protecting the identity of the server that physically processes the request.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A content-filtering web proxy server provides administrative control over the content that may be relayed in one or both directions through the proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] It is commonly used in both commercial and non-commercial organizations (especially schools) to ensure that Internet usage conforms to acceptable use policy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Content filtering proxy servers will often support user authentication to control web access.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] It also usually produces logs, either to give detailed information about the URLs accessed by specific users or to monitor bandwidth usage statistics.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] It may also communicate to daemon-based or ICAP-based antivirus software to provide security against viruses and other malware by scanning incoming content in real-time before it enters the network.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Many workplaces, schools, and colleges restrict websites and online services that are accessible and available in their buildings.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Governments also censor undesirable content.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This is done either with a specialized proxy, called a content filter (both commercial and free products are available), or by using a cache-extension protocol such as ICAP, which allows plug-in extensions to an open caching architecture.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Websites commonly used by students to circumvent filters and access blocked content often include a proxy, from which the user can then access the websites that the filter is trying to block.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Requests may be filtered by several methods, such as a URL or DNS blacklists, URL regex filtering, MIME filtering, or content keyword filtering.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Blacklists are often provided and maintained by web-filtering companies, often grouped into categories (pornography, gambling, shopping, social networks, etc.).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The proxy then fetches the content, assuming the requested URL is acceptable.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] At this point, a dynamic filter may be applied on the return path.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] For example, JPEG files could be blocked based on fleshtone matches, or language filters could dynamically detect unwanted language.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] If the content is rejected, then an HTTP fetch error may be returned to the requester.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Most web filtering companies use an internet-wide crawling robot that assesses the likelihood that content is a certain type.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Manual labor is used to correct the resultant database based on complaints or known flaws in the content-matching algorithms.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Some proxies scan outbound content, e.g., for data loss prevention, or scan content for malicious software.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Web filtering proxies are not able to peer inside secure sockets HTTP transactions, assuming the chain-of-trust of SSL/TLS (Transport Layer Security) has not been tampered with.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The SSL/TLS chain-of-trust relies on trusted root certificate authorities.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In a workplace setting where the client is managed by the organization, devices may be configured to trust a root certificate whose private key is known to the proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In such situations, proxy analysis of the contents of an SSL/TLS transaction becomes possible.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The proxy is effectively operating a man-in-the-middle attack, allowed by the client's trust of a root certificate that the proxy owns.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] If the destination server filters content based on the origin of the request, the use of a proxy can circumvent this filter.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] For example, a server using IP-based geolocation to restrict its service to a certain country can be accessed using a proxy located in that country to access the service.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Web proxies are the most common means of bypassing government censorship, although no more than 3% of Internet users use any circumvention tools.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Some proxy service providers allow businesses access to their proxy network for rerouting traffic for business intelligence purposes.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In some cases, users can circumvent proxies that filter using blacklists by using services designed to proxy information from a non-blacklisted location.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Proxies can be installed to eavesdrop upon the data-flow between client machines and the web.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] All content sent or accessed, including passwords submitted and cookies used, can be captured and analyzed by the proxy operator.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] For this reason, passwords to online services (such as webmail and banking) should always be exchanged over a cryptographically secured connection, such as SSL.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] By chaining the proxies that do not reveal data about the original requester, it is possible to obfuscate activities from the eyes of the user's destination.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] However, more traces will be left on the intermediate hops, which could be used or offered up to trace the user's activities.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] If the policies and administrators of these other proxies are unknown, the user may fall victim to a false sense of security just because those details are out of sight and mind.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In what is more of an inconvenience than a risk, proxy users may find themselves being blocked from certain websites, as numerous forums and websites block IP addresses from proxies known to have spammed or trolled the site.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Proxy bouncing can be used to maintain privacy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A **caching proxy** server accelerates service requests by retrieving the content saved from a previous request made by the same client or even other clients.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Caching proxies keep local copies of frequently requested resources, allowing large organizations to significantly reduce their upstream bandwidth usage and costs, while significantly increasing performance.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Most ISPs and large businesses have a caching proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Caching proxies were the first kind of proxy server.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Web proxies are commonly used to cache web pages from a web server.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Poorly implemented caching proxies can cause problems, such as an inability to use user authentication.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A proxy that is designed to mitigate specific link-related issues or degradation is a Performance Enhancing Proxy (PEPs).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] These are typically used to improve TCP performance in the presence of high round-trip times or high packet loss (such as wireless or mobile phone networks); or highly asymmetric links featuring very different upload and download rates.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] PEPs can make more efficient use of the network, for example, by merging TCP ACKs (acknowledgements) or compressing data sent at the application layer.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A translation proxy is a proxy server that is used to localize a website experience for different markets.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Traffic from the global audience is routed through the translation proxy to the source website.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] As visitors browse the proxied site, requests go back to the source site where pages are rendered.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The original language content in the response is replaced by the translated content as it passes back through the proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The translations used in a translation proxy can be either machine translation, human translation, or a combination of machine and human translation.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Different translation proxy implementations have different capabilities.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Some allow further customization of the source site for the local audiences, such as excluding the source content or substituting the source content with the original local content.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] An anonymous proxy server (sometimes called a web proxy) generally attempts to anonymize web surfing.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Anonymizers may be differentiated into several varieties.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The destination server (the server that ultimately satisfies the web request) receives requests from the anonymizing proxy server and thus does not receive information about the end user's address.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The requests are not anonymous to the anonymizing proxy server, however, and so a degree of trust is present between the proxy server and the user.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Many proxy servers are funded through a continuous advertising link to the user.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Advertisers use proxy servers for validating, checking, and quality assuring geotargeted ads.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A geotargeting ad server checks the request source IP address and uses a geo-IP database to determine the geographic source of requests.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Using a proxy server that is physically located inside a specific country or a city gives advertisers the ability to test geotargeted ads.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A proxy can keep the internal network structure of a company secret by using network address translation, which can help the security of the internal network.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This makes requests from machines and users on the local network anonymous.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Proxies can also be combined with firewalls.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] An incorrectly configured proxy can provide access to a network otherwise isolated from the Internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Proxies allow websites to make web requests to externally hosted resources (e.g., images, music files, etc.) when cross-domain restrictions prohibit the website from linking directly to the outside domains.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Proxies also allow the browser to make web requests to externally hosted content on behalf of a website when cross-domain restrictions (in place to protect websites from the likes of data theft) prohibit the browser from directly accessing the outside domains.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Secondary market brokers use web proxy servers to circumvent restrictions on online purchases of limited products such as limited sneakers or tickets.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The request from the client is the same as a regular HTTP request except the full URL is passed, instead of just the path.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This request is sent to the proxy server, the proxy makes the request specified, and returns the response.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Some web proxies allow the HTTP CONNECT method to set up forwarding of arbitrary data through the connection; a common policy is to only forward port 443 to allow HTTPS traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Examples of web proxy servers include Apache (with mod_proxy or Traffic Server), HAProxy, IIS configured as proxy (e.g., with Application Request Routing), Nginx, Privoxy, Squid, Varnish (reverse proxy only), WinGate, Ziproxy, Tinyproxy, RabbIT and Polipo.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] For clients, the problem of complex or multiple proxy-servers is solved by a client-server Proxy auto-config protocol (*PAC file*).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Various operating systems (such as Windows, Android, macOS, iOS, Xbox OS and PlayStation OS) and various browsers (such as Edge, Chrome, Safari and Firefox) can support Web proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] SOCKS also forwards arbitrary data after a connection phase, and is similar to HTTP CONNECT in web proxies.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] An **intercepting proxy** redirects or filters client traffic without being explicitly selected by the client.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] It is therefore often deployed without requiring browser or application proxy settings, and clients may be unaware that their traffic is passing through a proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In HTTP terminology, an interception proxy differs from a conventional HTTP proxy because it is not chosen by the user agent; instead, it is placed in the network path and filters or redirects outgoing traffic, commonly TCP port 80 traffic.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is a traffic filtering security feature that protects TCP servers from TCP SYN flood attacks, which are a type of denial-of-service attack.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] TCP Intercept is available for IP traffic only.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In 2009 a security flaw in the way that transparent proxies operate was published by Robert Auger, and the Computer Emergency Response Team issued an advisory listing dozens of affected transparent and intercepting proxy servers.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are commonly used in businesses to enforce acceptable use policies and to ease administrative overheads since no client browser configuration is required.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This second reason, however, is mitigated by features such as Active Directory group policy, or DHCP and automatic proxy detection.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Intercepting proxies are also commonly used by ISPs in some countries to save upstream bandwidth and improve customer response times by caching.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This is more common in countries where bandwidth is more limited (e.g, island nations) or must be paid for.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The diversion or interception of a TCP connection creates several issues.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] First, the original destination IP and port must somehow be communicated to the proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This is not always possible (e.g., where the gateway and proxy reside on different hosts).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] There is a class of cross-site attacks that depend on certain behaviors of intercepting proxies that do not check or have access to information about the original (intercepted) destination.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This problem may be resolved by using an integrated packet-level and application-level appliance or software, which is then able to communicate this information between the packet handler and the proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Intercepting also creates problems for HTTP authentication, especially connection-oriented authentication such as NTLM, as the client browser believes it is talking to a server rather than a proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This can cause problems where an intercepting proxy requires authentication, and then the user connects to a site that also requires authentication.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Finally, intercepting connections can cause problems for HTTP caches, as some requests and responses become uncacheable by a shared cache.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In integrated firewall/proxy servers where the router/firewall is on the same host as the proxy, communicating original destination information can be done by any method, for example, Microsoft TMG or WinGate.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Interception can also be performed using Cisco's WCCP (Web Cache Control Protocol).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This proprietary protocol resides on the router and is configured from the cache, allowing the cache to determine what ports and traffic are sent to it via transparent redirection from the router.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This redirection can occur in one of two ways: GRE tunneling (OSI Layer 3) or MAC rewrites (OSI Layer 2).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Once traffic reaches the proxy machine itself, interception is commonly performed with NAT (Network Address Translation).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Such setups are invisible to the client browser, but leave the proxy visible to the web server and other devices on the internet side of the proxy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Recent Linux and some BSD releases provide TPROXY (transparent proxy), which performs IP-level (OSI Layer 3) transparent interception and spoofing of outbound traffic, hiding the proxy IP address from other network devices.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A CGI web proxy accepts target URLs using a Web form in the user's browser window, processes the request, and returns the results to the user's browser.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Consequently, it can be used on a device or network that does not allow "true" proxy settings to be changed.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The first recorded CGI proxy, named "rover" at the time but renamed in 1998 to "CGIProxy", was developed by American computer scientist James Marshall in early 1996 for an article in "Unix Review" by Rich Morin.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The majority of CGI proxies are powered by one of CGIProxy (written in the Perl language), Glype (written in the PHP language), or PHProxy (written in the PHP language).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] As of April 2016, CGIProxy has received about two million downloads, Glype has received more than half a million downloads, whilst PHProxy still receives hundreds of downloads per week.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Despite waning in popularity due to VPNs and other privacy methods, as of September 2021 there are still a few hundred CGI proxies online.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Some CGI proxies were set up for purposes such as making websites more accessible to disabled people, but have since been shut down due to excessive traffic, usually caused by a third party advertising the service as a means to bypass local filtering.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Since many of these users do not care about the collateral damage they are causing, it became necessary for organizations to hide their proxies, disclosing the URLs only to those who take the trouble to contact the organization and demonstrate a genuine need.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A suffix proxy allows a user to access web content by appending the name of the proxy server to the URL of the requested content (e.g., "en.wikipedia.org.*SuffixProxy.com*").
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Suffix proxy servers are easier to use than regular proxy servers, but they do not offer high levels of anonymity, and their primary use is for bypassing web filters.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] However, this is rarely used due to more advanced web filters.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Tor is a system intended to provide online anonymity.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Tor client software routes Internet traffic through a worldwide volunteer network of servers for concealing a user's computer location or usage from someone conducting network surveillance or traffic analysis.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Using Tor makes tracing Internet activity more difficult, and is intended to protect users' personal freedom and their online privacy.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] This reduces the possibility of the original data being unscrambled or understood in transit.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The I2P anonymous network ('I2P') is a proxy network aiming at online anonymity.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] It implements garlic routing, which is an enhancement of Tor's onion routing.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] I2P is fully distributed and works by encrypting all communications in various layers and relaying them through a network of routers run by volunteers in various locations.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] By keeping the source of the information hidden, I2P offers censorship resistance.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The goals of I2P are to protect users' personal freedom, privacy, and ability to conduct confidential business.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Each user of I2P runs an I2P router on their computer (node).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The I2P router takes care of finding other peers and building anonymizing tunnels through them.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] I2P provides proxies for all protocols (HTTP, IRC, SOCKS, ...).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The proxy concept refers to a layer-7 application in the OSI reference model.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Network address translation (NAT) is similar to a proxy but operates in layer 3.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] In the client configuration of layer-3 NAT, configuring the gateway is sufficient.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] However, for the client configuration of a layer-7 proxy, the destination of the packets that the client generates must always be the proxy server (layer 7), then the proxy server reads each packet and finds out the true destination.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Because NAT operates at layer 3, it is less resource-intensive than the layer-7 proxy, but also less flexible.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] As we compare these two technologies, we might encounter a terminology known as 'transparent firewall'.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] **Transparent firewall** means that the proxy uses the layer-7 proxy advantages without the knowledge of the client.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The client presumes that the gateway is a NAT in layer 3, and it does not have any idea about the inside of the packet, but through this method, the layer-3 packets are sent to the layer-7 proxy for investigation.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A DNS proxy server takes DNS queries from a (usually local) network and forwards them to an Internet Domain Name Server.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Some client programs "SOCKS-ify" requests, which allows adaptation of any networked software to connect to external networks via certain types of proxy servers (mostly SOCKS).
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] A residential proxy (RESIP) is an intermediary that uses a real IP address provided by an Internet service provider with physical devices such as mobile phones and end-user computers.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Instead of connecting directly to a server, residential proxy users connect to the target through residential IP addresses.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] The target then identifies them as organic internet users.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] It does not let any tracking tool identify the reallocation of the user.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Any residential proxy can send any number of concurrent requests, and IP addresses are directly related to a specific region.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Unlike regular residential proxies, which hide the user's real IP address behind another IP address, rotating residential proxies, also known as *backconnect proxies*, conceal the user's real IP address behind a pool of proxies.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] These proxies switch between themselves at every session or at regular intervals.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Despite providers' assertions that the proxy hosts are voluntarily participating, numerous proxies are operated on potentially compromised hosts, including Internet of things devices.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] Through the process of cross-referencing the hosts, researchers have identified and analyzed logs that have been classified as potentially unwanted program and exposed a range of unauthorized activities conducted by RESIP hosts.
[src:firewall-concepts/proxy-server] These activities encompassed illegal promotion, fast fluxing, phishing, hosting malware, and more.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] In computing, a **stateful firewall** is a network-based firewall that individually tracks sessions of network connections traversing it.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] **Stateful packet inspection**, also referred to as dynamic packet filtering, is a security feature often used in non-commercial and business networks.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] A stateful firewall keeps track of the state of network connections, such as TCP streams, UDP datagrams, and ICMP messages, and can apply labels such as *LISTEN*, *ESTABLISHED*, or *CLOSING*.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] State table entries are created for TCP streams or UDP datagrams that are allowed to communicate through the firewall in accordance with the configured security policy.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] Once in the table, all *RELATED* packets of a stored session are streamlined, taking fewer CPU cycles than standard inspection.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] Related packets are also permitted to return through the firewall even if no rule is configured to allow communications from that host.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] If no traffic is seen for a specified time (time-out implementation dependent), the connection is removed from the state table.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] This can lead to applications experiencing unexpected disconnects or half-open TCP connections.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] Applications can be written to send keepalive messages periodically to prevent a firewall from dropping the connection during periods of no activity or for applications which by design have long periods of silence.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] The method of maintaining a session's state depends on the transport protocol being used.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] TCP is a connection-oriented protocol and sessions are established with a three-way handshake using *SYN* packets and ended by sending a *FIN* notification.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] The firewall can use these unique connection identifiers to know when to remove a session from the state table without waiting for a timeout.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] UDP is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not send unique connection-related identifiers while communicating.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] Because of that, a session will only be removed from the state table after the configured time-out.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] UDP hole punching is a technology that leverages this trait to allow for dynamically setting up data tunnels over the internet.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] ICMP messages are distinct from TCP and UDP and communicate control information of the network itself.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] A well-known example of this is the ping utility.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] ICMP responses will be allowed back through the firewall.
[src:firewall-concepts/stateful-firewall] In some scenarios, UDP communication can use ICMP to provide information about the state of the session so ICMP responses related to a UDP session will also be allowed back through.
